Constructor Detail

ShardedSessionFactoryImpl

public ShardedSessionFactoryImpl(List<ShardId> shardIds,
                                 Map<org.hibernate.engine.SessionFactoryImplementor,Set<ShardId>> sessionFactoryShardIdMap,
                                 ShardStrategyFactory shardStrategyFactory,
                                 Set<Class<?>> classesWithoutTopLevelSaveSupport,
                                 boolean checkAllAssociatedObjectsForDifferentShards)
Constructs a ShardedSessionFactoryImpl

Parameters:
shardIds - The ids of the shards with which this SessionFactory should be associated.
sessionFactoryShardIdMap - Mapping of SessionFactories to shard ids. When using virtual shards, this map associates SessionFactories (physical shards) with virtual shards (shard ids). Map cannot be empty. Map keys cannot be null. Map values cannot be null or empty.
shardStrategyFactory - factory that knows how to create the ShardStrategy that will be used for all shard-related operations
classesWithoutTopLevelSaveSupport - All classes that cannot be saved as top-level objects
checkAllAssociatedObjectsForDifferentShards - Flag that controls whether or not we do full cross-shard relationshp checking (very slow)

openSession

public org.hibernate.classic.Session openSession(Connection connection)
Unsupported. This is a technical decision. We would need a ShardedConnection in order to make this work, but since this method is exposed on the public api we can't force clients to provide it. And at any rate, exposing a ShardedConnection somewhat defeats the purpose of tucking away all the sharding intelligence.

Specified by:
openSession in interface org.hibernate.SessionFactory

getSessionFactory

public ShardedSessionFactory getSessionFactory(List<ShardId> shardIds,
                                               ShardStrategyFactory shardStrategyFactory)
Constructs a ShardedSessionFactory that operates on the given list of shardIds. This operation is relatively lightweight as the returned ShardedSessionFactory reuses existing shards. Most common use will be to provide a ShardedSessionFactory that manages a subset of the application's shards.
